    "summary": "This dissertation consists of three chapters, unified by a central inquiry into how institutional changes and policy shifts shape economic outcomes and social equity in China. Each chapter examines a distinct policy transformation—family planning, labor market reform, and trade liberalization—through the lens of inequality, mobility, and power. While the contexts differ, the overarching theme is clear: the distributional consequences of economic policies are profoundly mediated by social norms, political incentives, and pre-existing structures of advantage."
